Hurricane Andrew, which killed 15 people and left a quarter of a million people  homeless in south Florida, hit sparsely populated farming communities and swampland  in Louisiana killing two people and injuring less than 100.
Most Louisiana oil refineries  were not affected.
In Florida local officials were critical of delays in supplying food,  drinking water, and other supplies to thousands in need.
Transportation Secretary  Andrew Card promised "dramatic" improvements within 24 hours and President Bush  ordered troops to Florida.
The government estimated it would cost $20 billion to $30  billion to rebuild in Florida and care for those displaced by the storm. 
